The '''Battle of Westerplatte''' was one of the first battles in Germany's [[invasion of Poland]], marking the start of [[World War II]] in [[Europe]]. Beginning on 1 September 1939, [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|army]], [[Kriegsmarine|naval]] and [[Luftwaffe|air forces]] and [[Free City of Danzig Police|Danzig police]] assaulted  [[Poland]]'s Military Transit Depot (''Wojskowa Składnica Tranzytowa'', or ''WST'') on the [[Westerplatte]] peninsula in the harbor of the [[Free City of Danzig]]. The Poles held out for seven days and repelled 13 assaults that included [[dive bomber|dive-bomber]] attacks and naval shelling.

Westerplatte's defense served as an inspiration for the [[Polish Army]] and people in the face of German advances elsewhere, and is still regarded as a symbol of resistance in modern Poland.

==Background==
Westerplatte is a peninsula in the [[Bay of Gdańsk]].<ref name="LerskiLerski1996">{{cite book|author1=Jerzy Jan Lerski|author2=George J. Lerski|author3=Halina T. Lerski|title=Historical Dictionary of Poland, 966–1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QTUTqE2difgC&pg=PA646|year=1996|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-26007-0}}</ref>{{rp|646}} Following the reestablishment of Polish independence after [[aftermath of World War I|World War I]], much of the surrounding region became part of [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]]. However, the city of Danzig (present-day [[Gdańsk]], Poland), historically an important port city, became an independent [[city-state]], the [[Free City of Danzig]]. The Free City was nominally supervised by the [[League of Nations]] but, over time, Danzig became increasingly allied with Germany, reflecting its predominantly ethnic German population.<ref name="Parish2009">{{cite book|author=Matthew Parish|title=Free City in the Balkans: Reconstructing a Divided Society in Bosnia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mzQBAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA210|date=30 October 2009|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-0-85771-273-8}}</ref>{{rp|210}}<ref name="Fox2008">{{cite book|author=Gregory H . Fox|title=Humanitarian Occupation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nqEtn_nFmyEC&pg=PA21|date=21 February 2008|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-46973-9}}</ref>{{rp|21}}

In 1921, in the wake of the [[Polish-Soviet War]], the League of Nations granted Poland the right to install a [[garrison]]ed [[ammunition depot]] near Gdańsk.<ref name="JanOsm">{{cite book|author1=Edmund Jan·Osma鈔czyk|author2=Edmund Jan Osmańczyk|author3=Rupert Lee|title=Encyclopedia of the United Nations and International Agreements: T to Z|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hSxS2MmQsewC&pg=PA2684|year=2003|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-93924-9}}</ref>{{rp|2684}} Despite  objections from the Free City, this right was confirmed in 1925, and an area of {{convert|60|ha|m2|lk=in}} was selected on the Westerplatte peninsula.<ref name="JanOsm"/><ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://muzeum1939.pl/en/exhibition-westerplatte/845.html|title=Exhibition on Westerplatte|last=Garba|first=Bartłomiej|last2=Westphal|first2=Marcin|date=2017-03-30|website=muzeum1939.pl|publisher=Museum of the Second World War|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref><ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|443}} Westerplatte was separated from the New Port of the [[Free City of Danzig]] mainly by the [[harbour|harbor]] channel; on land, the Polish-held part of Westerplatte was separated from Danzig's territory by a brick wall topped with barbed wire.<ref name=":0" />{{rp|443}}<ref name="Komorowski2009" /> A dedicated rail line, passing through the Free City, connected the depot with nearby Polish territory.<ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|443}} The depot, referred to in League documents as the {{ill|Depot for Polish Munitions in Transit in the Port of Danzig|pl|Wojskowa Składnica Tranzytowa}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=QIS1wIZmWl0C&q=%22Depot+for+Polish+Munitions+in+Transit+in+the+Port+of+Danzig%22&dq=%22Depot+for+Polish+Munitions+in+Transit+in+the+Port+of+Danzig%22|title=Report to the ... Assembly of the League on the Work of the Council, on the Work of the Secretariat and on the Measures Taken to Execute the Decisions of the Assembly|last=|first=|date=1926|isbn=|location=|language=en}}</ref>{{rp|45}} ({{lang-pl|Wojskowa Składnica Tranzytowa}}), was completed in November 1925, officially transferred to Poland on the last day of that year, and became operational shortly after in January 1926, with 22 active storage warehouses. The Polish garrison's complement was set at 88 soldiers (2 officers, 20 [[Non-commissioned officer|NCO]]s, and the rest [[private (rank)|private]]s), and Poland was prohibited construction of further military installations or fortifications on the site.<ref name=":0" /><ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|443–444}}

By early 1933, German politicians and media figures complained about the need for border adjustments.  In addition, Polish and French discussed the need for a [[preventive war]] against Germany.  On 6 March 1933, in what became known as the "Westerplatte incident" or "crisis", the Polish government landed a marine battalion on Westerplatte, briefly reinforcing the outpost to about 200 men, demonstrating Polish resolve to defend the outpost; more locally, the Polish maneuver was also intended to put pressure on the Danzig government, which was trying to renounce a prior agreement on shared Danzig-Polish control over the harbor police and to acquire full control of the police and the harbor.<ref name="Weinberg2010" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Crockett|first=Jameson W.|date=2009|title=The Polish Blitz, More than a Mere Footnote to History: Poland and Preventive War with Germany, 1933|journal=Diplomacy & Statecraft|volume=20|issue=4|pages=561–579|doi=10.1080/09592290903455667}}</ref> The additional Polish troops were withdrawn on 16 March 1933, following protests from the League, Danzig, and Germany, but only in exchange for Danzig's withdrawal of its objections to the harbor-police agreement.<ref name="Weinberg2010">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o5FiQbU_nAkC&pg=PA50|title=Hitler's Foreign Policy 1933–1939: The Road to World War II|author=Gerhard L. Weinberg|date=1 March 2010|publisher=Enigma Books|isbn=978-1-929631-91-9}}</ref>{{rp|50}} According to another source, on 14 March 1933 the League had authorized Poland to reinforce its garrison.<ref name="JanOsm" />

Over subsequent years, the Poles constructed clandestine [[fortification]]s on Westerplatte.<ref name=":0" />  These were not impressive: there were no [[bunker]]s or tunnels, only several small outposts (guardhouses), partially hidden in the peninsula's forest, and several more buildings in the peninsula's center, including [[barracks]]. Most buildings were constructed with [[reinforced concrete]], and were supported by a network of field fortifications ([[trench]]es, [[barricade]]s, and [[barbed wire]]).<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":4" /><ref name=Zaloga>{{cite book|author=Steven J. Zaloga|title=Poland 1939: The birth of Blitzkrieg|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W8Q-vgAACAAJ|date=19 August 2002|publisher=Bloomsbury USA|isbn=978-1-84176-408-5}}</ref>{{rp|54}}

==Prelude==
In March 1939, a [[1939 German ultimatum to Lithuania|German ultimatum to Lithuania]] led to Germany's annexation of the nearby Lithuanian coastal [[Klaipėda region]]; subsequently, the Westerplatte garrison was placed on alert.<ref name=":0" /><ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|445}} Fearing a possible Nazi ''[[coup d'etat]]'' in Danzig, the Poles decided to secretly reinforce their garrison<ref name=":0" /><ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|445}} and, for that purpose, resorted to a subterfuge: civilians in Polish Army uniform would leave the base, and new Polish soldiers would enter it.<ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|445}}

By late August 1939, the Poles had reinforced their 88-man garrison, though its strength is still debated; older sources speak of 182 men, but more recent research suggests something in the range of 210 to 240, including six officers: [[Major]] [[Henryk Sucharski]], [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]] [[Franciszek Dąbrowski]], Captain {{ill|Mieczysław Słaby|pl|Mieczysław Słaby}} [[Poruchik|Lieutenant]] {{ill|Leon Pająk|pl|Leon Pająk}}, Lieutenant {{ill|Stefan Ludwik Grodecki|pl|Stefan Ludwik Grodecki}}, and [[Podporucznik|Second Lieutenant]] {{ill|Zdzisław Kręgielski|pl|Zdzisław Kręgielski}}.<ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|445}}<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dróżdż|first=Krzysztof Henryk|date=2013|title=Przyczynek do badań nad stanem liczbowym załogi Wojskowej Składnicy Tranzytowej na Westerplatte we wrześniu 1939 roku|trans-title=Addendum to the studies on the numbers of personnel the Westerplatte Military Depot in September 1939|url=http://bazhum.muzhp.pl/media//files/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy-r2013-t14(65)-n2_(244)/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy-r2013-t14(65)-n2_(244)-s196-200/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy-r2013-t14(65)-n2_(244)-s196-200.pdf|journal=Przegląd Historyczno-Wojskowy|language=Polish|volume=14(65)/2 (244)|pages=196–200|via=}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Jan|first=Szkudliński|date=2012|title=Spór w sprawie białej flagi nad Westerplatte|trans-title=Debate regarding the white flag at Westerplatte|url=http://bazhum.muzhp.pl/media//files/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy-r2012-t13_(64)-n4_(242)/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy-r2012-t13_(64)-n4_(242)-s153-163/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy-r2012-t13_(64)-n4_(242)-s153-163.pdf|journal=Przegląd Historyczno-Wojskowy|language=Polish|volume=13 (64)/4 (242)|pages=153–163|via=}}</ref> Estimates include some 20 mobilized civilians and about 10 regular troops who happened to be on site when fighting began.<ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|445}} In addition to light arms (pistols, grenades, and about 160 rifles), weaponry included a {{ill|75 mm field gun wz. 1902/26|pl|75 mm armata wz. 1902/26}}, two antitank [[Bofors 37 mm]] guns, four {{ill|81 mm mortars|pl|81 mm moździerz piechoty wz. 31}}, and about 40 machine guns, including 18 heavy ones.<ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|446}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mhmg.pl/oddzial/13/westerplatte|title=Westerplatte|last=|first=|date=|website=www.mhmg.pl|publisher=Muzeum Historyczne Miasta Gdańska|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141310/http://www.mhmg.pl/oddzial/13/westerplatte|archive-date=2018-06-12|access-date=2018-06-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> Field fortifications were extended: more trenches were dug, wooden barricades were built, barbed wire was strung into [[wire obstacle]]s, and reinforced concrete shelters were built into the basements of the barracks.  Foliage was thinned to reduce cover from expected avenues of attack.<ref name=":0" /><ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|446}}<ref name=Mann/>{{rp|11–12}}

The Polish defense, which anticipated principally a German land-based assault, rested on three lines of defense. The outer line included entrenchments which were to hold long enough for the garrison to mobilize. The second line of defense centered on the six outposts. The final defense comprised the headquarters and barracks at the depot's center.<ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|445}} The plan called for Westerplatte to hold out for 12 hours, after which the siege was expected to be lifted by Polish reinforcements arriving from the mainland.<ref name=Lask/>

On 25 August 1939 the German [[pre-dreadnought battleship]] {{SMS|Schleswig-Holstein||2}}, under the pretext of making a [[courtesy call]], sailed into [[Port of Gdańsk|Danzig harbor]],<ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|446}} anchoring {{convert|164|yd|m}} from Westerplatte. On board was a ''[[Marinestosstruppkompanie]]'' (marine shock-troop company) with orders to launch an attack on Westerplatte on the morning of 26 August 1939. For their planned attack on Westerplatte, the Germans had an ''[[SS Heimwehr Danzig]]'' force of 1,500 men under Police General [[Friedrich-Georg Eberhardt]], and the 225 [[marine (military)|marines]] under [[Lieutenant]] [[Wilhelm Henningsen]]. In overall command was Captain [[Gustav Kleikamp]], aboard the ''Schleswig-Holstein''. On 26 August he moved the battleship farther upstream. Major Sucharski, commanding Westerplatte, put his garrison on heightened alert.<ref name=Mann/>{{rp|12}} Shortly before the German disembarkation, the orders were rescinded. [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] had postponed hostilities on learning of the [[Polish-British Common Defence Pact]], signed the day before, on 25 August 1939, and that Italy was hesitant about its obligations under the [[Pact of Steel]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Janusz Piekałkiewicz|authorlink=Janusz Piekałkiewicz|title=Sea War, 1939–1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DEogAAAAMAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Historical Times|isbn=978-0-918678-17-1}}</ref>{{rp|18}}

Neither General Eberhardt nor Captain Kleikamp had specific information on the Polish defenses.<ref name=":2">{{Cite journal|last=Szkudliński|first=Jan|date=2015|title=Wojskowa składnica tranzytowa na Westerplatte w świetle nowych niemieckich materiałów archiwalnych|trans-title=Westerplatte Military Depot in light of the new German archival materials|url=http://bazhum.muzhp.pl/media//files/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy-r2015-t16_(67)-n3_(253)/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy-r2015-t16_(67)-n3_(253)-s141-159/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy-r2015-t16_(67)-n3_(253)-s141-159.pdf|journal=Przegląd Historyczno-Wojskowy|language=Polish|volume=16 (67)/3 (253)|pages=141–159|via=}}</ref> The Germans assumed that preliminary bombardment would soften up the fortifications enough for the marines to capture Westerplatte.<ref name=DGW>{{cite book|author=David G. Williamson|title=Poland Betrayed: The Nazi-Soviet Invasions of 1939|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wtg8a-0ggkEC|year=2011|publisher=Stackpole Books|isbn=978-0-8117-0828-9}}</ref>{{rp|66}} Reportedly Captain Kleikamp had been assured by the [[Free City of Danzig Police|Danzig police]] that "Westerplatte would be taken in 10 minutes."<ref>{{cite book|author=Richard Hargreaves|title=Blitzkrieg Unleashed: The German Invasion of Poland, 1939|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lTW_dftTTUcC&pg=PA120|year=2010|publisher=Stackpole Books|isbn=978-0-8117-0724-4}}</ref>{{rp|120}} General Eberhardt himself was more cautious, estimating that "a few hours" would be needed to overcome the Polish garrison, which the Germans estimated at no more than 100 men.<ref name=Lask/>

==Battle==
[[File:Westerplatte en.PNG|thumb|right|400px|Map of the battle]]
On the early morning of 1 September 1939, the ''Schleswig-Holstein'' suddenly fired a broadside salvo at the Polish garrison. That salvo's time has been variously stated as 04:45,<ref name="Zabecki2015"/><ref name="Paterson2015"/> 04:47,<ref>{{cite book  | last = Williamson  | first = Gordon  | year = 2003  | title = German Battleships 1939–45  | publisher = Osprey Publishing  | location = Oxford  | isbn = 978-1-84176-498-6  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=z-3w7JSYHD4C&printsec=frontcover  }}</ref>{{rp|5–6}} or 04:48.<ref name="Komorowski2009"/>{{rp|446}}<ref name="Tuliszka2003">{{cite book|author=Jarosław Tuliszka|title=Westerplatte 1926–1939: dzieje Wojskowej Składnicy Tranzytowej w Wolnym Mieście Gdańsku|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1XYjAQAAMAAJ|year=2003|publisher=Wydawn. Adam Marszałek|isbn=978-83-7322-504-6}}</ref>{{rp|8, 152}} Polish historian [[Jarosław Tuliszka]] explains that 04:45 was the planned time, 04:47 was the time the order was given by Kleikamp, and 04:48 was the time the guns actually fired.<ref name="Tuliszka2003"/>{{rp|152}}  Shortly after, on Westerplatte, Major Sucharski radioed the [[Hel Fortified Area|nearby Polish military base]] on the [[Hel Peninsula]], "SOS: I'm under fire."<ref name=Mann>{{cite book|author=Parragon, Incorporated|title=Great Battles of World War II|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8cU_NAAACAAJ|year=2008|publisher=Parragon|isbn=978-1-4075-2513-6}}</ref>{{rp|12}}

Eight minutes later Lieutenant Wilhelm Henningsen's marines from the ''Schleswig-Holstein'' advanced, expecting an easy victory over the Poles.<ref name=Lask/> A Polish soldier, [[Staff Sergeant]] [[Wojciech Najsarek]], was killed by [[Machine Gun|machine-gun fire]], the first combat casualty of the battle and perhaps of the war.<ref name="Kurier">{{cite journal | author =Teresa Masłowska |date=September 2007 | title =Wojenne drogi polskich kolejarzy | journal =Kurier PKP | volume =2007 | issue =35 | pages =10 | id = | url =http://www.pkp.pl/files/09-14.pdf | accessdate = | quote =Wojciech Najsarek był jedną z pierwszych ofiar II wojny światowej. |language=pl}}</ref><ref name="Drzycimski1990">{{cite book|author=Andrzej Drzycimski|title=Major Henryk Sucharski|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6oRJAAAAIAAJ|year=1990|publisher=Zakład Narodowy im. Ossolińskich|isbn=978-83-04-03374-0|quote=st. sierż. Wojciech Najsarek, zawiadowca stacji, poległ jako pierwszy z żołnierzy Składnicy, na posterunku, na stacji PKP Westerplatte}}</ref>{{rp|140}} However, soon after crossing the artillery-breached brick wall, the Germans stepped into an [[ambush]]. They found themselves in a [[kill zone]] of Polish crossfire from concealed firing positions (they believed they were also fired on by [[sniper]]s in the trees, but that was not so), while [[barbed wire|barbed-wire]] entanglements impeded their movements. The Poles knocked out a German ''[[Schutzpolizei (Nazi Germany)|Schutzpolizei]]'' machine-gun nest, and Lt. Leon Pająk opened intense howitzer fire on the advancing Germans, who faltered and broke off their attack. The single 75&nbsp;mm field gun fired 28 shots, knocking out several machine-gun nests atop warehouses across the harbor canal, before it was destroyed by the battleship's guns.<ref name=Mann/>{{rp|12}}

At 06:22 the German marines frantically radioed the battleship that they had sustained heavy losses and were withdrawing. The Danzig police had tried to seize control of the harbor on the other side of Westerplatte, but had been defeated. Casualties were approximately 50 Germans and eight Poles, mostly wounded.<ref name=Mann/>{{rp|13}} A longer bombardment from the battleship, lasting from 07:40 to 08:55, preceded a second attack.<ref name=Lask/> The Germans tried again from 08:35 to 12:30<ref name=Lask/> but encountered mines, felled trees, barbed wire, and intense fire.<ref name=Mann/>{{rp|13}} By noon the Germans retreated, Henningsen gravely wounded.<ref name=Lask/>

On the first day's combat, the Polish side had sustained four killed and several wounded.<ref name="Komorowski2009"/>{{rp|446}} The German marines had lost 16 killed and some 120 wounded.<ref name=Lask>{{cite journal|last=Laskowski|first=Piotr|date=2008|title=Kompania szturmowa Kriegsmarine w walkach na Westerplatte 1939 r|trans-title=Assault company of Kriegsmarine in the battle of Westerplatte in 1939|url=http://www.okretywojenne.pl/pefu/westbatterie/images/2008b/kompania_szturmowa.pdf|journal=Przegląd Morski|language=Polish|volume=9|pages=55–63|via=}}</ref>

<!--[[File:Schleswig Holstein ostrzeliwuje Westerplatte 39 09 01 b.jpg|thumb|right|200px|''[[Schleswig-Holstein (battleship)|Schleswig-Holstein]]'' fires at [[Westerplatte]]]]-->
The German commanders concluded that a ground attack was not feasible until the Polish defenses had been softened.<ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|443}} Re-examining aerial photographs, where they had previously underestimated Polish defenses, they now overestimated them, concluding the Poles had constructed extensive underground and armored fortifications (six haystacks were declared to be armored bunker domes).<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wprost.pl/80278/Koniec-mitu-Westerplatte|title=Koniec mitu Westerplatte|last=Piński|first=Jan|date=2005-09-04|work=WPROST.pl|access-date=2018-07-06|last2=Przedmojski|first2=Rafał|language=pl-PL}}</ref> In the following days, the Germans bombarded the Westerplatte peninsula with [[naval artillery|naval]] and heavy [[field artillery]], including a 105&nbsp;mm [[howitzer]] battery and 210&nbsp;mm mortars.<ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|447}} On 2 September, from 18:05 to 18:25,<ref name=Lask/> a two-wave air raid by 60 [[Junkers Ju 87]] ''[[Stuka]]'' [[dive bomber]]s dropped 26.5 tons of bombs,<ref name="Komorowski2009"/>{{rp|446}} taking out the Polish mortars, destroying Outpost Five with a 500&nbsp;kg bomb, and killing at least eight Polish soldiers; the air raid shrouded all of Westerplatte in clouds of smoke and destroyed the Poles' only radio and much of their food supplies.<ref name=Mann/>{{rp|13}} According to some German sources, after the air raid the Poles briefly displayed a white flag; but not all historians are convinced of this, and the German observers may have been mistaken.<ref name=":1" /><ref name=Lask/><ref name=":2" />

On 4 September, a [[German torpedo boats of World War II|German torpedo boat]], the ''[[T196]]'', supported by an old minesweeper, the ''Von der Gronen'' (formerly {{SMS|M107|1918|2}}), made a surprise attack from the sea side.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rohwer|first1=Jürgen| last2= Hümmelchen |first2=Gerhard|title= Chronology of the War at Sea 1939–1945|year=1992|publisher=Greenhill Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-85367-117-3}}</ref>{{rp|3}} The Poles' ''Wał'' post had been abandoned, and now only the ''Fort'' position prevented an attack from the north.<ref name=Mann/>{{rp|14}} Though the Poles never landed a hit on the German naval units, the ''T196'' and the ''Schleswig-Holstein'' suffered accidents due to crew error or equipment failure, with at least several injured men and at least one fatality on the battleship.<ref name=":2" />

On 5 September Major Sucharski held a conference with his officers, during which he urged surrender: the post had only been supposed to hold out for twelve hours.<ref name=Mann/>{{rp|11,14}} His deputy, Captain [[Franciszek Dąbrowski]], opposed surrender and the group decided to hold out a while longer.<ref name=Mann/>{{rp|14}}

<!---[[File:Westerplatte Sucharski sabre.jpg|thumb|left|[[Henryk Sucharski|Major Sucharski]] (''right'', with [[szabla|saber]]) on 7 September 1939 surrenders [[Westerplatte]] to General Eberhardt.]]-->
Subsequently, the Poles repelled several cautious German probing attacks by the marines, Danzig ''[[SS]]'' and police, and ''[[Wehrmacht]]''. At 03:00 on 6 September, during one of the attacks, the Germans sent a burning train toward the land bridge, but the ploy failed when the terrified driver decoupled prematurely.<ref name=Mann/>{{rp|14}} The train failed to reach the oil cistern and set fire to the woods, which had provided the Poles with valuable cover. In addition, the flaming wagons created a perfect field of fire, and the Germans suffered heavy losses. A second fire-train attack, in the afternoon, likewise failed.<ref name=Mann/>{{rp|15}}
[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-2008-0513-500, Danzig, Westerplatte, Wald.jpg|thumb|German soldiers on [[Westerplatte]], 8 September, after the battle]]
At a second conference with his officers, on 6 September, Sucharski was again ready to surrender: the German Army was by now outside [[Warsaw]], and Westerplatte was running critically low on supplies; moreover, many of the wounded were suffering from [[gangrene]].<ref name=Mann/>{{rp|15}} At 04:30 on 7 September the Germans opened intense fire on Westerplatte which lasted till 07:00. Flamethrowers and bombardment destroyed Outpost Two and damaged Outposts One and Four.<ref name=Mann/>{{rp|15}} The ''Schleswig-Holstein'' took part in the bombardments.<ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|447}}

At 09:45 on 7 September 1939 a white flag appeared.  The Polish defense had so impressed the Germans that their commander, General Eberhardt, let Sucharski keep his ceremonial ''[[szabla]]'' (Polish [[saber]]) in captivity<ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|447}} (it was, however, confiscated later).<ref name=Mann/>{{rp|15}} Contemporary English-language publications (such as ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' and the ''Pictorial History of the War'') misidentified the Polish commander as a Major "Koscianski".<ref>{{cite news|author=|work=Life|title=Heroic Polish Defense of Westerplatte Ends as Nazi Mop-up of Poland Begins|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QkIEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA30|date=9 October 1939|page=30|issn=0024-3019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Hutchinson|first1=Walter|title=Pictorial History of the War (Volume 1)|date=1939|publisher=Virtue and Company Ltd|pages=89}}</ref>

Sucharski surrendered the post to Captain Kleikamp, and the Germans stood at attention as the Polish garrison marched out at 11:30.<ref name=Mann/>{{rp|15}} Over 3,000 Germans (soldiers and support formations such as the Danzig police) had been tied up in the week-long operation against the small Polish garrison; about half of the Germans (570 on land, over 900 at sea) had taken part in direct action. German casualties totaled 50 killed (16 from Kriegsmarine<ref name=Lask/>) and 150 wounded.<ref name="Komorowski2009"/>{{rp|447}} The Poles had lost 15 men and had sustained at least 40 wounded.<ref name="Komorowski2009">{{cite book|author=Krzysztof Komorowski|title=Boje polskie 1939–1945: przewodnik encyklopedyczny|chapter=Westerplatte (1–7 IX 1939)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QLydUSWHEm0C|year=2009|publisher=Bellona|isbn=978-83-11-10357-3}}</ref>{{rp|447}}<ref name=Lask/>

==Aftermath==
[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-1989-516-505, Westerplatte, hissen der Reichskriegsflagge.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Reichskriegsflagge|German war flag]] being raised on [[Westerplatte]], 8 September 1939]]

On 8 September, the day after the capitulation, the Germans discovered a grave with the bodies of four unidentified Polish soldiers who had been executed by their comrades for attempted [[desertion]].  This had likely taken place following the 2 September air raids.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sudoł|first=Tomasz|date=2013|title=Tajemnica Westerplatte|url=http://pamiec.pl/download/49/30538/Tajemnica_Westerplatte__22013.pdf|journal=Pamięć.pl|language=Polish|volume=2|pages=14–15|via=}}</ref>

Five days after the capitulation, on 12 September 1939, the Polish wireless operator, [[sergeant]] Kazimierz Rasiński, was murdered by the Germans.  He was shot after brutal interrogation during which he refused to hand over radio codes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mhmg.pl/lista/zaloga-westerplatte/293/rasinski-kazimierz-sierz-rez/193|title=Rasiński Kazimierz sierż rez|website=www.mhmg.pl|publisher=Muzeum Historyczne Miasta Gdańska|language=en|access-date=2018-06-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621143648/http://mhmg.pl/lista/zaloga-westerplatte/293/rasinski-kazimierz-sierz-rez/193|archive-date=2018-06-21|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J_VmAAAAMAAJ|title=Battle of the Baltic: The Wars 1918–1945|author=Robert Jackson|publisher=Pen & Sword Maritime|year=2007|isbn=978-1-84415-422-7}}</ref>{{rp|55}}

On 19 September [[Adolf Hitler]] came to visit Gdańsk.  While there, on 21 September, he inspected Westerplatte.<ref name=":0" />

Controversy surrounds the Polish garrison's commanding officer, [[Henryk Sucharski|Major Henryk Sucharski]], and his [[executive officer]], Captain [[Franciszek Dąbrowski]]. Early historiography considered Major Sucharski to have been in command throughout the battle, and consequently early accounts   portrayed him as a heroic figure. More recent accounts from the early 1990s have presented evidence that Sucharski's officers had vowed not to disclose in their lifetimes that their commander had been [[shell-shock]]ed for most of the battle and had advocated surrender as early as 2 September, and several times thereafter; and that Captain Dąbrowski had effectively taken command following Sucharski's breakdown on the second day of the siege.<ref name=":3" /><ref name=doct/>{{rp|153}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://histmag.org/major-henryk-sucharski-wojskowy-z-tajemnica-13841/1|title=Major Henryk Sucharski: wojskowy z tajemnicą|last=Kwiatkowski|first=Mikołaj|date=2016-08-30|work=Histmag.org|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref><ref name="Derdej2009">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=La5KfmIfGv8C&pg=PA8|title=Westerplatte, Oksywie, Hel 1939|author=Piotr Derdej|publisher=Bellona|year=2009|pages=8|language=Polish|id=GGKEY:XBT004NC99S}}</ref> Sucharski's conduct is still debated by historians.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wyborcza.pl/alehistoria/1,121681,16550762,Tajemnica_majora_Sucharskiego.html|title=Tajemnica majora Sucharskiego|last=Maciorowski|first=Mirosław|date=1 September 2014|work=wyborcza.pl|access-date=2018-07-06|language=pl-PL}}</ref>

==Remembrance==
[[File:Westerplatte koszary 2.jpg|thumb|Ruins of Westerplatte barracks, 2005]]
[[File:79th anniversary of the outbreak of World War II (7).jpg|thumb|A Polish naval officer delivering an address during the 79th anniversary of the Battle of Westerplatte in 2018.]]
The Battle of Westerplatte is often described as the opening battle of [[World War II]],<ref name="Zabecki2015">{{cite book|author=David T. Zabecki|title=World War II in Europe: An Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mq_lCAAAQBAJ&pg=PT1663|date=1 May 2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-81242-3|quote=The earliest fighting started at 0445 hours when marines from the battleship Schleswig-Holstein attempted to storm a small Polish fort in Danzig, the Westerplate}}</ref>{{rp|1663}}<ref name="Paterson2015">{{cite book|author=Lawrence Paterson|title=Schnellboote: A Complete Operational History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w34ACwAAQBAJ&pg=PA19|date=30 November 2015|publisher=Seaforth Publishing|isbn=978-1-84832-083-3|quote=Two minutes later the old battleship Schleswig-Holstein opened World War Two by bombarding the Polish military transit depot at Westerplatte, Danzig}}</ref>{{rp|19}} but it was only one of many battles in the first phase of the [[German invasion of Poland]] known as the [[Battle of the Border]]. [[I. C. B. Dear]] described the ''Schleswig-Holstein'''s salvos as having occurred "minutes after ''Luftwaffe'' attacks on Polish airfields" and other targets.<ref name="Dear1995">{{cite book |author= Ian Dear |title= The Oxford guide to World War II |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=K6iLdPOQddAC |date=1 January 1995 |publisher= Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-534096-9}}</ref>{{rp|995}} A bridge in nearby [[Tczew]] had been bombed around 04:30 hours,<ref name="ZalogaMadej1990">{{cite book |author1=Steve Zaloga |author2= W. Victor Madej |title= The Polish Campaign, 1939 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=L1EpAQAAMAAJ |date= 31 December 1990 |publisher=Hippocrene Books |isbn= 978-0-87052-013-6}}</ref>{{rp|107}}<ref name="Weal2012">{{cite book |author= John Weal |title= Bf 109D/E Aces 1939–41 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=s7jvCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT4 |date= 20 October 2012 |publisher= Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn= 978-1-78200-526-1}}</ref>{{Rp|4–7}} and the [[false flag|false-flag]] [[Operation Himmler]] had begun hours earlier.<ref name="Wittmann2016">{{cite book|author=Anna M. Wittmann|title=Talking Conflict: The Loaded Language of Genocide, Political Violence, Terrorism, and Warfare|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lm91DQAAQBAJ&pg=PA83|date=5 December 2016|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-4408-3425-7}}</ref>{{rp|83}}

The Polish historian {{ill|Krzysztof Komorowski|pl|Krzysztof Komorowski (historyk)}} writes that "Westerplatte has become one of the symbols of the Polish struggle for independence, and is inscribed in the list of the most heroic battles of modern Europe."<ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|448}}

For both sides the battle had mostly political, rather than tactical, importance.<ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|447}} Still, it did tie up substantial German forces for much longer than anyone had expected, notably preventing the ''Schleswig-Holstein'' from lending fire support in the nearby [[battle of Hel|battles of Hel]] and [[battle of Gdynia|Gdynia]].<ref name="Komorowski2009" />{{rp|448}}

Westerplatte's defense inspired the Polish Army and people even as German advances continued elsewhere; beginning 1 September 1939, [[Polish Radio]] repeatedly broadcast the phrase that made Westerplatte an important symbol: ''"Westerplatte broni się jeszcze"'' ("Westerplatte fights on").<ref name=doct>{{Cite book|url=http://www.sbc.org.pl/Content/96273/doktorat3357.pdf|title=Westerplatte. Mechanizmy kształtowania się i funkcjonowania miejsca pamięci w latach 1945–1989|last=Zajączkowski|first=Krzysztof|publisher=Uniwersytet Śląski w Katowicach (doctoral thesis)|year=2013|isbn=|location=Katowice|pages=|language=Polish|trans-title=Westerplatte. Mechanisms of creation and functioning of places of memory in years 1945–1989}}</ref>{{rp|39, 53}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://muzhp.pl/pl/e/1980/kapitulacja-westerplatte|title=Kapitulacja Westerplatte - Muzeum Historii Polski|last=Cichocki|first=Paweł|date=|website=Muzeum Historii Polsk|language=pl|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref> On 16 September [[Konstanty Ildefons Gałczyński]] penned a poem, ''Pieśń o żołnierzach Westerplatte'' ("A Song of the Soldiers of Westerplatte"), voicing a [[Occupation of Poland (1939–1945)|subsequent]] myth that all of Westerplatte's defenders had died in the battle, fighting to the last man.<ref name=doct/>{{rp|51, 158}}<ref name="Gałczyńska1998">{{cite book|author=Kira Gałczyńska|title=Gałczyński|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j1JhAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=11 April 2011|year=1998|publisher=Wydawn. Dolnośląskie}}</ref>{{rp|99}} The battle became a symbol of resistance to the invasion – a Polish [[Thermopylae]].<ref name="Lerski1996">{{cite book|author=Jerzy Jan Lerski|title=Historical dictionary of Poland, 966–1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QTUTqE2difgC&pg=PA646|accessdate=11 April 2011|year=1996|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-26007-0}}</ref>{{rp|646}} As early as 1943, a [[Polish People's Army]] unit was named for Westerplatte's soldiers (the [[1st Armoured Brigade (Poland)|Polish 1st Armoured Brigade of the Defenders of Westerplatte]]).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Anduła|first=Kamil|date=|title=Udział 1 Warszawskiej Brygady Pancernej im. Bohaterów Westerplatte w walkach o Kępę Oksywską (30 marca-5 kwietnia 1945 r.)|trans-title=Participation of the Polish 1st Armoured Brigade of the Heroes of Westerplatte in the battle of Kępa Oksywska (30 March-5 April 1945)|url=http://bazhum.muzhp.pl/media//files/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy-r2012-t13_(64)-n3_(241)/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy-r2012-t13_(64)-n3_(241)-s43-62/Przeglad_Historyczno_Wojskowy-r2012-t13_(64)-n3_(241)-s43-62.pdf|journal=Przegląd Historyczno-Wojskowy|language=Polish|volume=13 (64)/3 (241)|pages=43–62|via=}}</ref> That same year the [[Polish Underground State]] named a street after Westerplatte; and the following year, during the 1944 [[Warsaw Uprising]], an insurgent stronghold was named ''Westerplatte''.<ref name=doct/>{{rp|58}}

The Polish 75&nbsp;mm field gun became one of Germany's first [[War trophy|war trophies]] of World War II, displayed on a column at [[Flensburg]]. After the war it was moved to stand before the [[Naval Academy Mürwik]].<ref name="Lask" />
[[File:Westerplatte-Denkmal Danzig 2010.jpg|thumb|right|[[Westerplatte Monument]]]]
Westerplatte's Outposts One, Three and Four, the power plant, and the barracks survived the war.<ref name=":4" /><ref name=doct/>{{rp|294}} In 1946 a [[Cemetery of the Defenders of Westerplatte]] and a [[Tomb of the Unknown Soldier]] were established on the peninsula; the cemetery was placed near the destroyed Outpost Five.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=doct/>{{rp|296}} During the early postwar Stalinist era, Westerplatte was presented as a symbol of Poland's prewar anticommunist government and was marginalized in official history; Dr. [[Mieczysław Słaby]], the garrison surgeon at Westerplatte, was arrested and tortured and died in the custody of the [[Ministry of Public Security (Poland)|Ministry of Public Security]] in 1948.<ref name=":4" /> After [[Polish October|the mid-1950s liberalization]], Westerplatte began to be used as a propaganda symbol; in 1956 the [[Polish Naval Academy]] was named for the "Heroes of Westerplatte", and that name began to be given to schools, streets, and other institutions.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=doct/>{{rp|298, 300}} In 1962 a Christian cross at the cemetery was replaced with a Soviet [[T-34]] tank, and the first government-organized remembrances began at Westerplatte.<ref name=":4" /><ref name=doct/>{{rp|302–304}} In 1966 a {{ill|Monument to the Defenders of the Coast|pl|Pomnik Obrońców Wybrzeża}}, also known as the "Historical Monument, Site of the Battle of Westerplatte", a 25-meter-tall [[obelisk]] atop a [[mound]], was erected at Westerplatte, set within a park, with smaller installations.<ref name=doct/>{{rp|308–311}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.zdiz.gda.pl/zdizgdansk/chapter_76059.asp|title=1 Pomnik Historii "POLE BITWY NA WESTERPLATTE" : Gdański Zarząd Dróg i Zieleni|last=ZDiZ|website=www.zdiz.gda.pl|language=pl|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref> Westerplatte became a popular tourist attraction.<ref name=doct/>{{rp|351}} Later Outpost One was relocated in order to save it from destruction in the construction of a new harbor channel.<ref name=":0" /> In 1971 Major Sucharski's grave was relocated to Westerplatte from his original burial in Italy.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=doct/>{{rp|319–322}} In 1974 a small museum was opened in the renovated Outpost One.<ref name=doct/>{{rp|326}} Since the 1980s Westerplatte has been administered by the [[National Museum, Gdańsk|National Museum in Gdańsk]].<ref name=":4">{{Cite web|url=https://muzeumgdansk.pl/oddzialy-muzeum/wartownia-nr1-westerplatte/|title=Wartownia Nr 1 Westerplatte|last=Gierszewski|first=Andrzej|date=2018-04-30|website=|publisher=Muzeum Gdańska|language=Polish|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 1981 the cross was restored to the cemetery.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=doct/>{{rp|334}} In June 1987 Westerplatte was visited by [[Pope John Paul II]];<ref name=doct/>{{rp|338}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.solidarnosc.gda.pl/aktualnosci/12-czerwca-1987-jan-pawel-ii-na-westerplatte/|title=12 czerwca 1987. Jan Paweł II na Westerplatte {{!}} Region Gdański NSZZ "Solidarność"Region Gdański NSZZ "Solidarność"|website=www.solidarnosc.gda.pl|language=pl-PL|access-date=2018-07-08|date=2018-06-12}}</ref> his visit is commemorated by a plaque unveiled in 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://gdansk.naszemiasto.pl/artykul/tablica-ze-slowami-papieza-jana-pawla-ii-na-westerplatte,3419841,artgal,t,id,tm.html|title=Tablica ze słowami papieża Jana Pawła II na Westerplatte [ZDJĘCIA]|last=Oleksy|first=Ewelina|date=2015-06-13|work=gdansk.naszemiasto.pl|access-date=2018-07-08|language=pl-PL}}</ref>  A change symbolic of Poland's political transformation was the removal of the Soviet T-34 tank from the cemetery (in 2007 the tank was moved to a museum in another town).<ref name=":0" /><ref name=doct/>{{rp|349–350}} In 2001 the Polish government recognized Westerplatte's ruins as an [[object of cultural heritage]].<ref>[https://www.nid.pl/pl/Informacje_ogolne/Zabytki_w_Polsce/rejestr-zabytkow/zestawienia-zabytkow-nieruchomych/stan%20na%2031.03.2016/POM-rej.pdf Official listing of objects of cultural heritage], NID (National Heritage Board of Poland)</ref> On 1 September 2003 the site was designated an official [[List of Historical Monuments (Poland)|Historic Monument]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nid.pl/pl/Informacje_ogolne/Zabytki_w_Polsce/Pomniki_historii/Lista_miejsc/miejsce.php?ID=278|title=Gdańsk – pole bitwy na Westerplatte|last=|first=|date=|website=www.nid.pl|publisher=Narodowy Instytut Dziedzictwa|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-06-21}}</ref> In the mid-2010s the Polish government decided to create a dedicated {{ill|Westerplatte Museum|pl|Muzeum Westerplatte i Wojny 1939}}, commemorating the 1939 battle; the museum is to open in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tvp.info/23725721/muzeum-westerplatte-i-wojny-1939-otwarcie-1-wrzesnia-2019-roku|title=Muzeum Westerplatte i Wojny 1939. Otwarcie 1 września 2019 roku|last=|first=|date=2016-01-23|work=TVP|access-date=2018-06-21|language=pl}}</ref>

Westerplatte is a common venue for remembrance ceremonies, usually held on 1 September, relating to World War II. They are generally attended by high-ranking Polish politicians such as Prime Minister [[Donald Tusk]] (2014),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wpolityce.pl/polityka/211722-westerplatte-tusk-jak-nie-tusk-dzis-nie-czas-na-piekne-przemowienia|title=Westerplatte. Tusk jak nie Tusk: dziś nie "czas na piękne przemówienia"|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref> President [[Bronisław Komorowski]] (2015),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tvp.info/19970456/komorowski-na-westerplatte-w-europie-sa-sily-ktore-daza-do-utrzymania-sasiadow-w-wasalnej-zaleznosci|title=Komorowski na Westerplatte: w Europie są siły, które dążą do utrzymania sąsiadów w wasalnej zależności|access-date=2018-07-08|language=pl}}</ref> President [[Andrzej Duda]] (2016),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tvn24.pl/wiadomosci-z-kraju,3/77-rocznica-rozpoczecia-ii-wojny-uroczystosci-na-westerplatte,672699.html|title=Nie można pozwolić na to, aby wracały w Europie działania i ambicje o charakterze imperialnym|work=TVN24.pl|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref> and Prime Minister [[Beata Szydło]] (2017).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wprost.pl/kraj/10073292/Musimy-przypominac-kto-byl-bohaterem-a-kto-katem-Premier-na-Westerplatte-w-78-rocznice-wybuchu-II-wojny-swiatowej.html|title="Musimy przypominać, kto był bohaterem, a kto katem". Premier na Westerplatte w 78. rocznicę wybuchu II wojny światowej|date=2017-09-01|work=WPROST.pl|access-date=2018-07-08|language=pl-PL}}</ref> The commemoration of the 70th anniversary of the outbreak of [[World War II]], in 2009, was attended by Prime Minister Tusk, former Prime Minister [[Tadeusz Mazowiecki]], and former Presidents [[Lech Wałęsa]] and [[Aleksander Kwaśniewski]], as well as by important figures from about 20 other countries, including German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]], Russian Prime Minister [[Vladimir Putin]], Ukrainian Prime Minister [[Yulia Tymoshenko]], and French Prime Minister [[François Fillon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wyborcza.pl/1,75398,6991440,Przeslanie_z_Westerplatte.html|title=Przesłanie z Westerplatte|last=Sandecki|first=Maciej|date=2009-09-02|website=wyborcza.pl|publisher=Wyborcza.pl|language=Polish|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-07-08}}</ref>

The Battle of Westerplatte has been the subject of two Polish films: ''[[Westerplatte (film)|Westerplatte]]'' (1967), and ''[[Tajemnica Westerplatte]]'' (The Secret of Westerplatte, 2013).<ref>{{IMDb title|1808518}}</ref> It has also inspired dozens of books and scores of press articles, scholarly studies, and fictional works, as well as poems, songs, paintings, and other works of art.<ref name=doct/>{{rp|3, 55}}

